# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: george-gibson-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The **1905 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1905.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended October 8, with the New York Giants and the Philadelphia Athletics as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the second modern World Series on October 9 and ended with Game 5 on October 14.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants defeated the Athletics, four games to one, capturing their first modern championship in franchise history.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Stung by criticism from fans and writers for his team's refusal to play in the previous season's World Series, Giants owner John T.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Brush drafted rules during the offseason to formally establish the World Series as a compulsory event.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Both leagues then adopted the agreement in mid-February 1905.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The 1905 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1904 season.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 16 with all but the Detroit Tigers and Cleveland Naps playing.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 8.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 9 and October 14.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing the Detroit Tigers, in a rescheduled game, to play at a ballpark in a different locality.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] 19 tie games (11 in AL, 8 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 9 and ended on October 14 with the New York Giants defeating the Philadelphia Athletics in the 1905 World Series in five games.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The Washington Senators' American League Park was renamed to National Park.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Due to horse races at main home ballpark, Bennett Park, the Detroit Tigers played two games at Neil Park in Columbus, Ohio, home of the Class A minor league Columbus Senators, on July 23 and 24.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **1905 Pittsburgh Pirates season** was the 24th season of the Pittsburgh Pirates franchise.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1905-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates finished second in the National League with a record of 96–57.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1907-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **1907 Pittsburgh Pirates season** was the 26th season for the Pittsburgh Pirates franchise.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1907-pittsburgh-pirates-season] It involved the Pirates finishing second in the National League.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1907-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The offense was led by Tommy Leach and Hall of Famers Honus Wagner and Fred Clarke.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1907-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Wagner led the NL in batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage, and stolen bases.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1907-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates scored the most runs of any team.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] The **1908 Chicago Cubs season** was the 37th season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 33rd in the National League, and the 16th at West Side Park.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] It involved the Cubs winning their third consecutive National League pennant, as well as the World Series for the second consecutive year.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] This team included four future Hall of Famers: manager / first baseman Frank Chance, second baseman Johnny Evers, shortstop Joe Tinker, and pitcher Mordecai Brown.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] In 1908, Brown finished second in the NL in wins and earned run average.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] This would be the last World Series victory for the Cubs until 2016; it would also take until 2003 – an MLB and North American professional sports record of 95 years – for the Cubs to win their next playoff series.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs started the season in Cincinnati.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Orval Overall was the Cubs' Opening Day starting pitcher.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Overall gave up five hits and committed an error in the first inning as the Reds took a 5–0 lead.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs tied the game in the sixth and won the game in the ninth.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Cubs pinch hitter Heinie Zimmerman drove in Johnny Evers.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Mordecai "Three Finger" Brown pitched in the ninth and got a save for the Cubs.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Owner Charles Murphy had added several new seats to the stadium.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Long-time Cub player-manager Cap Anson threw out the first pitch.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Tinker, Evers, and Chance turned their second double play of the season as the Cubs beat the Reds by a score of 7–3.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] On June 30, the Pittsburgh Pirates took first place, as the Cubs lost to the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Starting on July 2, the Pirates started a critical five game series against the Cubs.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] In the first game, Three Finger Brown threw a six hit, no walk shutout, winning the game 3–0.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] On September 26, starting pitcher Ed Reulbach became the only pitcher in Major League Baseball history to pitch two shutouts on the same day.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] That day, the Cubs played a doubleheader against the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Reulbach pitched both games to completion, which the Cubs won by scores of 5–0 and 3–0.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] In the bottom of the 9th inning, Merkle came to bat with two outs and the score tied 1–1.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] At the time, Moose McCormick was on first base.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Merkle singled, and McCormick advanced to third.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Al Bridwell followed with another single, and McCormick trotted home to score the apparent winning run.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] The New York fans in attendance, under the impression that the game was over, ran onto the field to celebrate.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Meanwhile, Merkle, thinking the game was over, ran to the Giants' clubhouse without touching second base (a gesture that was common at the time).
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Cubs second baseman Johnny Evers noticed this, and after retrieving a ball and touching second base, he appealed to umpire Hank O'Day to call Merkle out.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Since Merkle had not touched the base, the umpire called him out on a force play, and McCormick's run did not count.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] The run was therefore nullified, the Giants' victory erased, and the score of the game remained tied.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Unfortunately, the thousands of fans on the field (as well as the growing darkness in the days before large electric light rigs made night games possible) prevented resumption of the game, and the game was declared a tie.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] The Giants and the Cubs would end the season tied for first place and would have a rematch at the Polo Grounds on October 8.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs won this makeup game, 4–2, and thus the National League pennant.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] The **1908 New York Giants season** was the 26th season of the franchise.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in second place in the National League with a 98–56 record, one game behind the Chicago Cubs.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] Paced by Turkey Mike Donlin, the offense scored the most runs in the league.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] Donlin led the team in nearly all batting categories and was second in batting to Honus Wagner.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] Giants' pitching shut out the opposition 25 times, a franchise record for 1901 onwards.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] Future Hall of Famer Christy Mathewson earned the pitching triple crown with 37 wins, 259 strikeouts, and a 1.43 ERA.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] However, he lost the last game of the season to Three Finger Brown of the Chicago Cubs, and the Giants finished one game back in the pennant race.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] That one-game playoff became necessary after Giants rookie Fred Merkle failed to touch second base at the end of a previous contest, costing them a win.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] In addition, they were beaten by another rookie, Phillies pitcher Harry Coveleski, three times in five days late in the season.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] Coveleski was subsequently nicknamed "The Giant Killer".
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] The Giants opened the season on the road with a 3–1 victory over the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] The Giants took five of their first six games of the season.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] The home opener at the Polo Grounds was the biggest in club history, as the Giants attracted over 25,000 fans.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] The Brooklyn Superbas took a 2–1 lead into the bottom of the ninth.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] Fred Merkle pinch hit for Christy Mathewson and got a ground rule double.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] Merkle safely advanced to third base on a sacrifice bunt.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] Fred Tenney hit a grounder and Merkle was caught off third.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] Captain Donlin hit a two-run home run over the right field wall to win the home opener for the Giants by a score of 3–2.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] On July 4, Hooks Wiltse had a perfect game heading into the ninth inning.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] With two out in the ninth, the perfect game was still intact.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] George McQuillan was hit by a pitch and Wiltse lost the perfect game. on August 27, the Giants won 18 of their last 23 (including four in a row versus the Pittsburgh Pirates) to take the lead in the National League for the first time since April.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] During the Giants four-game sweep of the Pirates in late August, the electric scoreboard made its debut in New York.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] The first electric scoreboard was outside Madison Square Garden, and there was another near the Gotham Theatre on 125th Street.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] In the bottom of the 9th inning, he came up to bat with two outs, and the score tied 1–1.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] Al Bridwell, the next batter, followed with a single of his own.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] McCormick went home, apparently scoring the winning run of the game.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] The fans in attendance, under the impression that the game was over, ran onto the field to celebrate.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] Meanwhile, Merkle, trying to escape the mob of people, ran to the Giants' clubhouse without touching second base.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] The validity of the ball was disputed – numerous accounts have Giants pitcher Joe McGinnity intercepting the real ball before Evers could get it.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] However, since Merkle had not touched the base, the umpire called him out on a force play, and McCormick's run did not count.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] Since the run was nullified, the Giants' victory was erased, and the score of the game remained tied.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] Unfortunately, the thousands of fans on the field (as well as the growing darkness in the days before large electric light rigs made night games possible) prevented resumption of the game, and it was declared a tie.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] The Giants and the Cubs would end the season deadlocked atop the standings and would have a rematch at the Polo Grounds, on October 8.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] Giants manager John McGraw never blamed Merkle for the second-place finish.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-new-york-giants-season] However, the rookie was hounded by the New York press and fans for years thereafter.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **1908 Pittsburgh Pirates season** was the 27th season for the Pittsburgh Pirates franchise.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The team finished in a tie for second place in the National League with the New York Giants, one game behind the Chicago Cubs.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates spent 46 days in first place, and were on top on October 3; however, the team lost its last game to the Cubs, which set up a replay of the infamous "Merkle" game between the Cubs and the Giants.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Pittsburgh finished tied for second place with the Giants, just one game back.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] It was one of the closest races in baseball history.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Shortstop Honus Wagner had one of the most dominating hitting performances of all-time.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The "Flying Dutchman" led the majors in batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage, runs batted in, and stolen bases.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] He missed the triple crown by two home runs.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] For his efforts, Wagner was paid $5,000, possibly the most on the team.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates opened the season by winning three straight games in St.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] On Opening Day, the Pirates committed four errors while the Cardinals committed six.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Fans were concerned because Honus Wagner, who had led the National League in hitting, slugging, and stolen bases in 1907, was not at the game; many worried that he was taking the year off.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] On April 17, Charlie Starr, who was Wagner's replacement, committed two errors.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] After that game, Wagner signed with the Pirates.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The home opener for the Pirates was a 5–1 victory for the Pirates over the Cardinals.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] From April 26 to May 9, the Pirates played only 3 games due to poor weather.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] On June 30, the Pirates took first place, as the Chicago Cubs lost to the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] On July 2, the Pirates began a critical five-game series against the Cubs.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] During the first game, Mordecai Brown threw a six-hit, no-walk shutout, winning the game 3–0.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates scheduled a doubleheader on the Fourth of July and more than 30,000 fans showed up.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1908-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Cubs won the first game 2–0 as Mordecai Brown only allowed two hits.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] The **1909 Detroit Tigers** won the American League pennant with a record of 98–54, but lost to the Pittsburgh Pirates in the 1909 World Series, 4 games to 3.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] The season was their ninth since they were charter members of the American League in 1901.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] It was the third consecutive season in which they won the pennant but lost the World Series.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Center fielder Ty Cobb won the Triple Crown and pitcher George Mullin led the league in wins (29) and winning percentage (.784).
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Catching duties were split between Boss Schmidt (81 games) and Oscar Stanage (77 games).
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Schmidt hit .265 in 1908, but his batting average dropped to .209 in 1909.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] As a young man, Schmidt worked in the coal mines and was a skilled brawler who fought an exhibition match with the heavyweight champion, Jack Johnson.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Schmidt also beat Ty Cobb in at least two fights.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In the second fight, Schmidt knocked Cobb unconscious but admired Cobb's resiliency, and the two became friends until Schmidt's death in 1932.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Schmidt never wore shinguards and could force nails into the floor with his bare fists.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Stanage played for the Tigers from 1909 to 1920, catching 1,074 games for Detroit—second only to Bill Freehan in team history.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Stanage was a weak hitter but one of the best defensive catchers of the dead-ball era.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Known for his strong throwing arm, Stanage threw out more baserunners than any other catcher in the 1910s.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Stanage still holds the American League record for most assists by a catcher, with 212 in 1911, and his career average of 1.29 assists per game is the fifth best in major league history.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Stanage was not as skilled with the glove; his 41 errors in 1911 was the most by a catcher for the 20th Century.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] First baseman Claude Rossman played for the Tigers from 1907 to 1909.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In 1908, Rossman had the best year of his career with 33 doubles (2nd in the AL), 219 total bases (3rd in the AL), and 48 extra base hits (3rd in the AL).
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] On August 20, 1909, the Tigers traded him to the St.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Rossman had a peculiar emotional quirk where he sometimes froze and could not throw the ball when he became excited.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Runners would lead off first to draw a throw from the pitcher, then run to second when Rossman froze.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] He was 28 when he played his last major league game and died at age 46 in a New York hospital for the insane where he had been a patient for several years.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Second baseman Germany Schaefer was traded by the Tigers to the Washington Senators during the 1909 season for Jim Delahanty.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Schaefer is remembered more for his antics than for his performance on the field, including trying to steal first base (from second base) and, coming to bat in the rain with a raincoat and boots (to persuade the umpire to call the games).
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Schaefer was a pioneer of baseball clowning, and his vaudeville act with teammate Charley O'Leary was inspiration for the MGM musical film "*Take Me Out to the Ball Game*" starring Gene Kelly and Frank Sinatra.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In 1919, a little over a year after Schaefer played his last game, he died at age 42 of tuberculosis at the sanitarium in Saranac Lake, New York.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Jim Delahanty took over at second base from Schaefer in 1909.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] He played all seven games of the 1909 World Series, batting .346 with 4 runs batted in.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Donie Bush was Detroit's starting shortstop for thirteen seasons from 1909 to 1921.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] His 52 sacrifice hits is the fourth highest single season total in major league history.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] He also led the AL in walks in five times and walked more than any other major league player from 1910 to 1919.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Bush was also the surprise hitting star for Detroit in the World Series, hitting .318 with a .438 on-base percentage, picking up 7 hits, 5 bases on balls, 3 sacrifice hits, twice being hit by a pitch, scoring 5 runs and collecting 3 runs batted in.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Bush played all seven game of the World Series at shortstop, collecting 9 putouts, 18 assists, and 3 double plays (but also committing 5 errors).
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] George Moriarty hit .273 and stole 34 bases as the team's third baseman.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] He later became one of the AL's most highly regarded umpires, officiating in the World Series in 1921, 1925, 1930, 1933 and 1935.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Once while Moriarty was umpiring, Babe Ruth stepped out of the batter's box and asked Moriarty to spell his last name.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Charley O'Leary was Detroit's starting shortstop from 1904 to 1907 and became a backup shortstop and utility infielder from 1908 to 1912.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In 1908, he shared third baseman duties with Moriarty and hit .202.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] On September 30, 1934, O'Leary pinch hit for the St.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Louis Browns at age 51 and became one of the oldest players to collect a hit and score a run.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In 1909, Ty Cobb won the Triple Crown with a .377 batting average‚ nine home runs (all inside the park)‚ and 107 runs batted in.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] (He not only led the AL in all three Triple Crown categories; he led all major league players in all three categories.) Cobb also led the major leagues with 216 hits and 76 stolen bases.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Adding the stolen base title, Cobb was the only player ever to win a quadruple crown.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Right fielder Sam Crawford, known as "Wahoo Sam", was one of the greatest sluggers of the dead-ball era and still holds the major league records for triples in a career (309) and for inside-the-park home runs in a season (12) and a career (51).
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] He finished his career with 2,961 hits and a .309 batting average.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Crawford was among the AL leaders in hits, runs batted in, extra base hits, slugging percentage, and total bases every year for twelve consecutive years from 1905 to 1915.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Left fielder Matty McIntyre played for Detroit from 1904 to 1910.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] His best season was 1908, when he led the AL in: plate appearances (672), times on base (258), runs (105), and singles (131).
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] McIntyre is also remembered as the leader of the "anti-Cobb" clique on the Tigers during Cobb's early years.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Early in Cobb's rookie season, Cobb went after a flyball in McIntyre's left field territory.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] By cutting in front, Cobb caused McIntyre to drop the ball, infuriating McIntyre.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] McIntyre and his cohorts led a prolonged hazing campaign, locking Cobb out of an empty washroom, flicking food at Cobb, and nailing his shoes to the clubhouse floor.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Davy Jones played for the Tigers from 1906 to 1912.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] With Cobb and Crawford solidly entrenched in the outfield, Jones was forced to battle for the third outfield spot with McIntyre each year from 1906 to 1910.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] As a speedy leadoff man, he was a reliable run scorer with Cobb and Crawford following him in the lineup.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Jones' speed also made him a fine outfielder, with tremendous range.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In 1907, he led the AL with a .357 on-base percentage and finished second in the AL with 101 runs.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In his three World Series for the Tigers, Jones played in 18 games, had a .357 on-base percentage, scored 8 runs, and had a home run in the 1909 World Series against the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] George Mullin was the Tigers' leading pitcher in 1909, leading the major leagues with 29 wins and leading the AL with a .784 win percentage.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Mullin holds the Tigers franchise record for innings pitched (in a career and in a season) and has the second most wins in the team's history.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] He also pitched the team's first no-hitter; had five 20-win seasons (including a league-leading 29 wins in 1909); helped the Tigers to three straight American League pennants (1907–09); twice hit over .310 as a batter; and ranks 7th in major league history for fielding assists by a pitcher.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Ed Killian led the team (and was 4th in the AL) with a 1.71 ERA.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Twice a 20-game winner (including a 25–13 season in 1907), as of the end of the 2009 season Killian's career ERA of 2.38 is 26th-best in MLB history.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Killian also holds the record for fewest home runs allowed, giving up only 9 in his entire career.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] At one point, Killian pitched a record 1001 innings (from September 1903 – August 1907) without allowing a home run.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Ed Willett had his best season in 1909 when he had a record of 21–10, ranking 3rd in the American League in wins and 5th in winning percentage (.677).
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] He had an earned run average of 2.34 for the season and was among the AL leaders in games (41), innings (292+2⁄3), games started (34), complete games (25), bases on balls and hits allowed (88 and 239), as well as wild pitches (10) and hit batsmen (14).
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Ed Summers had two great seasons for the Tigers, going 24–12 with a 1.64 ERA in his 1908 rookie season, and 19–9 with a 2.24 ERA in 1909.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] On September 25, 1908, Summers threw two complete game victories in a double header to help the Tigers clinch the AL pennant.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] On July 16, 1909, Summers pitched 18 scoreless innings of a tie game against the Washington Senators at Bennett Park.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Bill Donovan was the Tigers ace in 1907 with a 25–4 record (the best win percentage in Tigers' team history), but in 1909 he went 8–7 in 17 starts.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] On May 7, 1906, Donovan stole second base, third base, and home on the front end of a double steal and also hit a triple in the same game.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In June 1923, Donovan died in a train wreck.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Ralph Works was a pitcher for Tigers from 1909 to 1912.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Works was called "Judge" by teammates for his scholarly countenance.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Works had career record of 24–24 with a 3.79 ERA.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] His best season was 1911 when he went 11–5 in 30 games for the Tigers.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] 5 in the American League in winning percentage (.688) in 1911, No.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Works died in of a self-inflicted gunshot would in Pasadena, California in 1941 at age 53.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] He died with his wife in an apparent double suicide.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Hughie "Ee-yah" Jennings led the Tigers to three consecutive American League pennants, in 1907–09.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Jennings continued to manage the Tigers through the 1920 season, though his team never won another pennant.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] During his years as Detroit's manager, Jennings became famous for his antics, mostly in the third base coaching box, which variously included shouts of "**Ee-Yah**", and other whoops, whistles, horns, gyrations, jigs, and grass-plucking.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] The "Ee-Yah" whoop became his trademark and was accompanied with waves of both arms over his head and a sharp raising of his right knee.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In 1907, he was suspended for taunting opponents with a tin whistle.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] The "Ee-Yah" shouts continued and became such a trademark that Jennings became known as Hughie "Ee-Yah" Jennings, and Detroit fans would shout "Eee-Yah" when Jennings would appear on the field.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Beyond his on-field behavior, Jennings was recognized for his managerial abilities.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Connie Mack described him as one of the three greatest managers in baseball history, alongside John McGraw and Joe McCarthy.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] The 1909 season was the third straight year the Tigers won the American League pennant.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Their 1909 record of 98–54 was the team's best record to that point.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Led by Ty Cobb, who won the Triple Crown and Sam Crawford, who led the league in doubles and extra base hits, they scored 66 more runs than any other team in the American League and outscored their opponents 666 to 493.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] They led the American League for most of the regular season, but remained in a close race with the Philadelphia Athletics, finally taking the pennant by 3½ games.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers faced the Pittsburgh Pirates‚ winners of 110 games‚ in the World Series.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] The Series matched AL batting champion Ty Cobb against NL batting champion Honus Wagner.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit gave up 18 stolen bases in 7 games to the Pirates.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 1, 27-year-old rookie Babe Adams faced George Mullin.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] There were only 11 hits in the game‚ but Fred Clarke's home run led the Pirates to a 4–1 win.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 2, Tigers' pitcher Bill Donovan led the team to a 7–2 win.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Ty Cobb stole home as the Tigers scored three runs in the third inning.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 3, the Pirates won, 8–6, behind three hits, three runs batted in and three stolen bases by Honus Wagner.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Nick Maddox was the winner over Ed Summers.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 4, George Mullin pitched a 5-hit shutout for Detroit, a 5–0 victory.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Ty Cobb drove in two runs with a double.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Mullin struck out ten batters, and the Pirates committed six errors.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 5, Pirates' rookie Babe Adams threw his second complete-game victory, an 8–4 win.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Sam Crawford hit a home run and a double, but Fred Clarke's three-run home run gave the win to Pittsburgh.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 6, George Mullin led the Tigers to a 5–4 win.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] The World Series would go to a seventh game for the first time.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 7, the Pirates won, 8–0, as Babe Adams got his third complete game victory of the 1909 World Series.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Adams was the only rookie pitcher in the 20th century to win a World Series Game 7.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] (John Lackey did it in 2002.) Fred Clarke walked four times, and Honus Wagner drove in two runs.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] The Pirates and Tigers combined for 34 errors (18 by the Tigers), a World Series record.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In November 1909, a group of players from the 1909 Tigers (not including Ty Cobb or Sam Crawford) toured Cuba and played 12 exhibition games against two integrated Cuban teams, Habana and Almendares.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] The Cuban-American Major League Clubs Series drew wide attention in Cuba, where baseball was already very popular.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] Demonstrating the high level of play in Cuba, the Tigers lost 8 of the 12 games to the integrated Cuban baseball teams.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] To take advantage of the interest in the tour of the American baseball players, the Cabañas Company printed a series of baseball cards showing the members of the Almendares, Habana and Detroit baseball teams.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] The Detroit roster, from a game played on November 18, 1909, consisted of the following players: Davy Jones, Charley O'Leary, George Moriarty, Matty McIntyre, Boss Schmidt, George Mullin, Heinie Beckendorf, Bill Hopke and W.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] In that game, Cuban pitcher, Eustaquio "Bombin" Pedroso no hit the Tigers for 11 innings‚ finally winning‚ 2–1.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] The only run for Detroit came on an error in the 7th inning.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] A squeeze bunt against Bill Lelivelt in the 11th inning scored the winner.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/1909-detroit-tigers-season] A collection was taken up for Pedroso and fans‚ including several Tigers‚ contributed 300 dollars.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson played during a period in baseball history known as the Dead-ball era and, was regarded as one of the National League's premier catchers because of his impressive defensive skills and his strong, accurate throwing arm.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] He was also known for his smart pitch-calling and his ability to hold runners on base.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] His reputation as a defensive standout is enhanced because of the era in which he played.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] In the deadball era, catchers played a huge defensive role, given the large number of bunts and stolen base attempts, as well as the difficulty of handling the spitball pitchers who dominated pitching staffs.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] He had to catch every type of pitch imaginable, such as shine balls, spitballs, knuckleballs, and emory balls.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson was inducted into Canada's Sports Hall of Fame in 1958, the Canadian Baseball Hall of Fame in 1987 and the London Sports Hall of Fame in 2002.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson was born in London, Ontario, near Tecumseh Park, the oldest continually operating baseball grounds in the world (today's Labatt Memorial Park).
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] He gained the nickname "Mooney" as a youngster.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Some sources suggest that the nickname was inspired by his round, moon-shaped face, while other sources claim he picked up the nickname because he had played on a sandlot team known as the Mooneys.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] He began his professional baseball career in 1903 with the Buffalo Bisons of the Eastern League, managed by George Stallings.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Numerous sources still associate Gibson with the Kingston Colonials of the Hudson River League but in a 1919 article, journalist Edward F.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Relaying something said by Gibson days earlier, he suggests that "somebody got him mixed with some other player shortly after he broke into the big league." George spent parts of two seasons playing for the Montreal Royals before his contract was purchased by the Pittsburgh Pirates in June 1905.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson made his major league debut July 2, 1905, at the age of 24.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson stood 5'11.5" and weighed 190 pounds, which was considered large for a baseball player of his era.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Although he did not provide prolific offensive statistics, he did provide excellent defensive abilities and was a keen student of baseball strategy under the tutelage of Pirates manager Fred Clarke.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] The Pirates finished in second place three times in four seasons between 1905 and 1908.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] During the 1908 season, they were involved in a tight pennant race with the Chicago Cubs and the New York Giants.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] The Pirates were in first place going into the final day of the season but lost their final game to the eventual National League champion Chicago Cubs.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson was in his prime during the 1909 season when he caught in 134 consecutive games, breaking the previous record of 133 consecutive games played as a catcher set by Deacon McGuire in 1895.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] He set another major league record for games played in a season by a catcher with 150, which was also previously held by McGuire since 1895.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] His games caught in a season record stood until 1920 when Ray Schalk caught 151 games.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] His record of 134 consecutive games caught would stand until 1940 when it was broken by Ray Mueller.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson hit a double for the final hit in the last game played at Pittsburgh's Exposition Park on June 29, 1909, and the following day had the first hit in the new Forbes Field.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson had a career-high 52 runs batted in and helped guide the Pirates' pitching staff to finish second in the league in shutouts as well as in earned run average as the team clinched the 1909 National League pennant.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] He also led National League catchers in fielding percentage, baserunners caught stealing and in caught stealing percentage.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson then went on to catch every game in the 1909 World Series as the Pirates defeated the Detroit Tigers in seven games to win the world championship.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson held Detroit's Ty Cobb, the premier base stealer of his era, to only one stolen base during the series (Cobb also stole home plate during the series which wasn't charged against Gibson).
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Arriving back at the train station in his hometown of London, Ontario, on October 27, 1909, after winning the World Series, Gibson found more than 7,000 cheering fans to greet him.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] At the time, the population of London was approximately 35,000.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson was a workhorse during his career with the Pirates, leading National League catchers in games played for four consecutive seasons between 1907 and 1910.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] When Gibson began his major league career, most catchers were large, bulky men, however as baseball progressed during the Deadball era, the decrease in run production placed greater significance on stolen bases and bunts, which in turn emphasized the crucial defensive role played by catchers.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] As the sport evolved, teams began to field smaller, more agile players as catchers, typified by the emergence of Ray Schalk.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] A newspaper article of the day referred to Gibson as being part of the "dreadnought" type.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] He suffered a broken ankle in late-April of 1913 and missed two months of the season.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson returned to hit for a career-high .285 batting average in 102 games during the 1914 season.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] In August 1916 the 36-year-old Gibson was placed on waivers and claimed by the New York Giants, but he refused to report that year.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Giants manager John McGraw persuaded him to join the Giants as a player-coach in 1917.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson played in his final major league game on August 20, 1918 at the age of 38.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] In a fourteen-year major league career, Gibson played in 1,213 games, accumulating 893 hits in 3,776 at bats for a .236 career batting average along with 15 home runs, 346 runs batted in and an on-base percentage of .295.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] He had a .977 career fielding percentage as a catcher which was 7 points higher than the league average for catchers during his career.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] He led all National League catchers in fielding percentage three times (1909, 1910, and 1912).
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson caught 124 shutouts during his career, ranking him 7th all-time among major league catchers.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson was the Pirates catcher on September 20, 1907, when pitcher Nick Maddox threw a no-hitter against the Brooklyn Superbas.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] In his book, *The Bill James Historical Baseball Abstract*, baseball historian Bill James ranked Gibson 95th all-time among major league catchers.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson is also said to have accepted a coaching position with the Sacramento Solons of the Pacific Coast League in 1918.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] This can be traced at least as far back as a *Sporting News* article from 1933, which notes that he agreed to terms with the club, but does not specify a position.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] This isn't true, and rather, Gibson, the catcher, is likely being confused with an amateur pitcher of the same name.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson, the catcher, remained with the Giants until the 1918 season closed because of World War I, and returned to Canada until he was hired in 1919 to coach the Toronto Maple Leafs of the International League.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] In December 1919, Gibson was named the new manager of the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] He served as their manager from 1920 to 1922.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] He then spent the 1923 season as a coach for the Washington Senators.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] In 1925, he became a coach for the Chicago Cubs, but finished the season as manager after Rabbit Maranville was dismissed.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] The following season (1926), he returned to his coaching capacities for the Cubs, then remained with the Cubs as a scout until he was again called upon by the Pirates, to manage the 1932 team.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Although Gibson recorded a .546 winning percentage as a manager, he was intolerant of team mistakes and his temperament left him ill-suited for the task of team politics.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] On June 19, 1934, the Pirates replaced Gibson with Pie Traynor.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] On May 9, 1921, under manager Gibson, the Pittsburgh Pirates beat the London Tecumsehs 8–7 at Tecumseh Park before 3,500 people in an exhibition baseball game.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Before the game, Gibson and his team were presented with a silver loving cup by the London Kiwanis Club.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson thrilled the locals by catching the opening inning with his 1909 battery-mate Babe Adams and singling and scoring a run in his lone at-bat.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] London Mayor Sid Little entertained the team that evening at his home.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson was named Canada's baseball player of the half century in 1958 and was the first baseball player elected to Canada's Sports Hall of Fame.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] He was subsequently inducted into the Canadian Baseball Hall of Fame & Museum in the Class of 1987 and was one of the inaugural 10 inductees into the London Sports Hall of Fame in 2002.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] In February 1955 while organizers were planning the charter season of the Eager Beaver Baseball Association, Gibson was named "honorary lifetime president." Today, there is a commemorative plaque prominently displayed at the entrance to the main grandstand at Labatt Park in Gibson's honour.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] An interview of Gibson was included as a chapter in the 1966 baseball book, *The Glory of Their Times*, written by Lawrence Ritter.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] When Gibson lived at 252 Central Avenue in London during the 1920s and 1930s, his immediate neighbours to the east were members of the Labatt brewing family, with whom he frequently socialized.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson died at age 86 in London and is buried at Campbell Cemetery in Komoka, Ontario, not far from his Delaware farm.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson's former farm is on a road named in his honour after Gibson donated some land for public use to the area conservation authority of the day.
[src:george-gibson-baseball/george-gibson-baseball] Gibson was the nephew of William Southam, founder of Southam Newspapers, the brother of Richard Southam, manager of the London Tecumsehs, and the father-in-law of Bill Warwick, a major league baseball player in the 1920s.
